-- 
Crude Oil Volatility Increases as Futures Fall to One-Week Low

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-03-28T21:12:10Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-28/crude-oil-volatility-increases-as-futures-fall-to-one-week-low.html
Oil options volatility increased as
the underlying futures dropped to the lowest level in a week.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
May, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 31.4 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New York , up
from 30.8 percent March 25. It was 35.8 percent a week ago.  Crude for May delivery fell $1.42, or 1.4 percent, to
settle at $103.98 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange ,
the biggest decline since March 15. Prices have gained 30
percent in the past year.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
May $110 calls with 2,642 lots changing hands. They fell 54
cents to 87 cents a barrel. May $100 puts, the next most active
contract, gained 25 cents to $1.26 a barrel with 1,238 contracts
trading. One contract is for 1,000 barrels of oil.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  May $125 calls were the most active options traded March
25, with 5,227 lots changing hands. They lost 5 cents to 17
cents a barrel. The next most active option, May $115 calls,
dropped 18 cents to 61 cents on 4,612 lots.  Open interest was highest for December 2012 $80 puts with
39,138 contracts. Next were December $100 calls with 38,917 and
June $150 calls with 38,630.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 